  "body": " For a given predicate , you might believe that the statements or are either true or false. How would you decide if you were correct in each case? You have four choices: you could give an example of an element in the domain for which is true or for which if false, or you could argue that no matter what is, is true or is false.   What would you need to do to prove is true?    What would you need to do to prove is false?    What would you need to do to prove is true?    What would you need to do to prove is false?         The claim that means that is true no matter what you consider in the domain of discourse. Thus the only way to prove that is true is to check or otherwise argue that is true for all in the domain.    To prove is false all you need is one example of an element in the domain for which is false. This is often called a counterexample .    We are simply claiming that there is some element in the domain of discourse for which is true. If you can find one such element, you have verified the claim.    Here we are claiming that no element we find will make true. The only way to be sure of this is to verify that every element of the domain makes false. Note that the level of proof needed for this statement is the same as to prove that is true.     "
